Here's what I tried:
```rust
fn convert(exc: anyhow::Error) -> Result<i32, MyError> {
    MyError { value: exc.to_string(), extra: "converted".into() }
}
```
But it panics at compile time because anyhow::Error doesn't implement From<MyError>.

You'll want a proper enum defined with thiserror, then use the ? operator to propagate. For example:
```rust
#[derive(Debug, thiserror::Error)]
enum MyError { thiserror!(From<anyhow::Error> value), }
fn convert(exc: anyhow::Error) -> Result<i32, MyError> {
    Ok(42)
}
// usage
let res = try_convert(&anyhow::Error::new("orig", "msg"));
```

Define an enum that derives From<HTTPStatus> and also implements From<anyhow::Error>. Use the ? operator in your handler:
```rust
enum ServerError { thiserror!(From<HTTPStatus> status), thiserror!(From<anyhow::Error> err), }
fn handle_request() -> Result<(), ServerError> {
    match get_status() {
        Ok(s) => if s != 200 { Err(ServerError::from(s)) } else { Ok(())
                },
        Err(e) => Err(ServerError::from_any(e)),
    }
}
```
This keeps both the original status and any additional context.
